{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e193213-19fc-4eaa-aff3-7a6078c56944","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. File I/O During Evaluation (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nProperty functions that perform file I/O execute during *evaluation*, not build. This blocks the evaluation phase with disk access. Prefer reading files via a target at build time instead.\n\n## 2. Expensive Recursive Glob (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nA double-star recursive glob (`**\\*.*`) forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This gets worse as the repo grows. Scope the glob to specific directories/extensions if possible.\n\n## 3. Deeply Chained Imports (Low–Medium Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of nested `<Import>` create a chain that adds cumulative file-open overhead during evaluation. While small here, this pattern scales poorly in real repos with many transitive imports.\n\n**Summary:** The biggest wins would come from (1) moving the `ReadAllText` call into a build target and (2) narrowing the recursive glob pattern.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c82c4e14-133d-4992-81bb-3d5b5a8c3975","outputTokens":346,"requestId":"284C:5FB6B:1D41CAA:207FF2C:69FA958F"},"id":"2bd432d0-725c-4a4d-aad4-5e022a272824","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:12:56.789Z","parentId":"a3253409-d980-4c15-a98e-7cfada9003fc"}
